The women’s rights group, Association des Femmes de Guinée pour le Développement (AFGD), is working to change this. AFGD is a grassroots organization that works to empower women and girls in Guinea through education, health, and economic development. AFGD’s programs include a women’s center, a school for girls, and a microfinance program. AFGD also works to raise awareness about women’s rights and gender-based violence. AFGD’s programs are run by a team of 15 women, including the Executive Director, the Director of Programs, and the Director of Finance. AFGD’s programs are funded by grants from the United Nations Development Program, the United Nations Population Fund, and the United Nations Children’s Fund. AFGD also receives funding from the Guinean government and from private donors.

The Guinean government has made some progress in addressing gender-based violence, but there is still a long way to go. In 2014, the government passed a law that criminalized domestic violence, but the law has not been implemented. In 2015, the government passed a law that criminalized marital rape, but the law has not been implemented.
